# CRDTs vs Operational Transformation: A Practical Comparison

## Quick Answer for Your Situation

**For a small team building from scratch: Use CRDTs** (specifically Yjs or Automerge libraries).

Here's why, with a deep technical comparison:

---

## Fundamental Difference

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    OPERATIONAL TRANSFORMATION                   │
│                                                                 │
│   Client A: insert('x', pos=5) ──┐                              │
│                                  ├──► Server transforms ops     │
│   Client B: delete(pos=3) ──────┘    against each other        │
│                                                                 │
│   Server must see ALL operations to transform correctly         │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                           CRDTs                                 │
│                                                                 │
│   Client A: insert('x', id=A1, after=B3) ──┐                    │
│                                            ├──► Merge anywhere  │
│   Client B: delete(id=B2) ────────────────┘    (no server!)    │
│                                                                 │
│   Operations are designed to merge automatically                │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

---

## Technical Deep Dive

### Operational Transformation (OT)

```javascript
// OT Example: Transform concurrent operations
class OTEngine {
  // The core challenge: transforming operations
  transform(op1, op2) {
    // op1: insert 'a' at position 5
    // op2: delete character at position 3

    // If op2 happened first, op1's position shifts!
    if (op2.type === 'delete' && op2.pos < op1.pos) {
      return { ...op1, pos: op1.pos - 1 };
    }
    if (op2.type === 'insert' && op2.pos <= op1.pos) {
      return { ...op1, pos: op1.pos + 1 };
    }
    return op1;
  }

  // Server must maintain operation history and transform
  // This gets VERY complex with multiple clients
  transformAgainstHistory(op, history) {
    let transformed = op;
    for (const historicOp of history) {
      transformed = this.transform(transformed, historicOp);
    }
    return transformed;
  }
}

// The problem: transformation functions are notoriously hard
// Google Docs team spent YEARS getting this right
// Academic papers have found bugs in published OT algorithms
```

### CRDTs (Conflict-free Replicated Data Types)

```javascript
// CRDT Example: Unique IDs make operations commutative
class SimpleCRDTText {
  constructor(siteId) {
    this.siteId = siteId;
    this.counter = 0;
    this.chars = []; // Array of { id, char, visible }
  }

  // Generate globally unique, ordered ID
  generateId(afterId) {
    this.counter++;
    return {
      site: this.siteId,
      counter: this.counter,
      // Position is between previous and next
      position: this.calculatePosition(afterId)
    };
  }

  insert(char, afterId) {
    const id = this.generateId(afterId);
    const op = { type: 'insert', id, char, afterId };
    this.applyLocal(op);
    return op; // Broadcast this
  }

  delete(id) {
    // Tombstone - mark as deleted, don't remove
    const op = { type: 'delete', id };
